post_text: What a GREAT day to be a Wildcat!! Today we went to Mission Valley for our first meet of the season and FOUR of our eight runners brought home some hardware! Sophomore Teagan Hines and Sophomore Taylor Pringle were 5th and 9th respectively in the Girls‚Äô Varisty Race. Soph Kylee White and Freshman Bethany DeDonder rounded out our squad with STELLAR performances for the first meet. On the boys‚Äô side, Junior Jerrod Campbell snatches the 3rd place medal with Freshman Cooper Hamlin right behind in 4th. Senior Ryder McGuire and Sophomore Grady Tiffany we‚Äôre both under 22:00 for their time so our boys are off to a great start, as well! Runners running is my favorite thing! üñ§ü§ç ~ Coach Lanzrath

post_text:
Northern Heights football team will open their season Friday night @ Council Grove.

This year will be very different for our athletes, but we are excited that they get to play! Each school will have their own regulations and each week we will share them out. We understand that this will be hard for some of our fans who enjoy following our teams, but we want to respect each school and follow their guidelines.

Council Grove- Limitations are, attendee has to be mom/dad, stepmom/stepdad, and siblings that are school aged or younger (k-12 or younger). They are not allowing college (or older) siblings or grandparents unless they are the legal guardian.

If you are not able to attend this game, please support our Wildcats from home: http://sports9.sport-lovers.org/hsfootball.php?live=Council%20Grove%20vs%20Northern%20Heights

On Saturday, Northern Heights held their long awaited graduation ceremony for the class of 2020. With this, came a few more memories these young adults can take with them as they officially leave the hallways of Northern Heights High School: meaningful speeches, the wind blowing caps off their heads, Taylor ‚Äúfalling‚Äù off the stage, and Kermit‚Äôs epic diploma toss at Mrs. Fort.

‚ÄúWe cannot change what has happened to us, but we can change how we react and how we live in the future. Living with no regrets is living successfully.‚Äù ~Dr. Ellen Taricani

Congratulations to the class of 2020!

On Saturday, Northern Heights held their long awaited graduation ceremony for the class of 2020. With this, came a few more memories these young adults can take with them as they officially leave the hallways of Northern Heights High School: meaningful speeches, the wind blowing caps off their heads, Taylor ‚Äúfalling‚Äù off the stage, and Kermit‚Äôs epic diploma toss at Mrs. Fort.

‚ÄúWe cannot change what has happened to us, but we can change how we react and how we live in the future. Living with no regrets is living successfully.‚Äù ~Dr. Ellen Taricani

post_text: This afternoon our North Lyon County USD 251 administrative team had a work session to watch the KSDE Zoom training pertaining to the 1,000 plus page Navigating Change Guidance document. We also finalized our agenda for our Re-Opening School team of teachers, staff, administration, parents, and board members that will meet on July 20th. Families, thank you for your patience, we will have our plan coming out soon!

post_text: Wanted to give an update about the upcoming NLC KickStart and Kindergarten Jumpstart programs that are on the calendar to start before school. Mr. Blair and I have been working the last three days to prepare a plan, based on the KSDE Navigating Change Guidance Document, that we have just submitted to the Lyon County Health Department to review and approve. So the plan is, even with the Governor's order of starting school after Labor Day, to continue with Kick Start and Jumpstart as scheduled so long as our precautionary plans are approved by the Lyon County Health Dept. We hope to hear soon so we can notify parents as soon as possible. We appreciate your patience and understanding during this time.

post_text:
We regret to inform you that the 251 Physical Night, that was postponed to August 5th, has now been cancelled due to safety concerns. Students must have a current physical (completed after May 1), which is typically free with insurance, so we encourage each family to make an appt with their primary health care provider to complete this to ensure your child can participate in school sports. IMPORTANT: There is an updated physical form that your physician must complete as only this updated form can be accepted. Please ask or take in the copy found at the below link to ensure the most up to date form is used.
http://www.kshsaa.org/public/pdf/form-ppe.pdf

post_text: The date for the 2020 8th grade trip to Worlds of Fun is Friday, July 24th. It is open from 11am - 7 pm. Due to COVID regulations, the school cannot transport your 8th grader to and from Worlds of Fun. You would be responsible for transportation. Also, Worlds of Fun regulations requires everyone attending to wear a mask at all times while on the park grounds. We need to find out who still wants to attend after hearing these changes. Please comment on here or email Aimee Landgren at landgrena@usd251.org if you are still wanting to attend and how many tickets you would need (including your 8th grade student). The 8th grade student‚Äôs ticket will be covered by the class fundraiser money. Thank you to the parents who have already responded. Please respond by tomorrow, Wednesday.

post_text: Weights and Conditioning start tomorrow morning. Please take your temperature before you leave your house, remember your waiver, and bring a water bottle.
shared_text:
USD 251 North Lyon County
June 8 at 12:57 PM ¬∑

Attached are the groups and times for Summer Weights and Conditioning. We did our best getting students in the time slots they requested. Americus sessions will be held at the City Park. Sessions are Mon-Thur.
PLEASE ONLY ATTEND THE SESSION YOU ARE ASSIGNED TO.

~ Bring your signed waiver or you will not be allowed to participate (thanks for those who have mailed them in).
~Bring your own water bottle.
~Please take your temperature each day. If it is above 100.3¬∞ or you don't feel well, please stay home.
~Stay in your vehicle until the coach motions you over, no congregating.

Please remember- KSHSSA has implemented a 10 day acclimatization period. All students need to attend 10 days (15 for football players) of conditioning in order to attend any sports camps or drills.

post_text:
What are you doing this summer? Welcome to Greenbush Summer Camp!
Greenbush Summer Camps Grades 1-8 (completed)

We‚Äôre going to miss our on-site campers this year, but that doesn‚Äôt mean we can‚Äôt camp digitally! Greenbush is hosting FREE virtual summer camps with a Passport to Learning. Campers will be given the opportunity to explore hobbies, earn badges, and learn valuable skills that inspire creativity!

About Our Camps
Using our unique combination of facilities, including a cutting-edge science center, world-class astrophysical observatory, and a camp and retreat center, Greenbush offers camp learning experiences unavailable anywhere else. We are able to offer these experiences at a price well below cost thanks to the donors who contribute each year to our educational foundation, The Learning Tree Institute at Greenbush. Our goal is to ensure dynamic learning opportunities are affordable and accessible. https://vimeo.com/421088491

Council Grove Braves Wrestling
April 6 at 10:08 AM ¬∑

Council Grove wrestling fans. We have some exciting news about our high school wrestlers. The Kansas Wrestling Coaches Association has announced their academic award winners.

The Council Grove Boys Wrestling Team earned 1st Team on the Kansas Wrestling Coaches Association Team Academic Championship for the 2019-2020 season. A team must have a minimum of 7 wrestlers competing in regionals to be eligible for an award. To be named to the first team, a team must have a cumulative GPA of 3.2 or above.

The Braves had four wrestlers earn individual academic awards. You must be a Junior or Senior to be eligible for the individual awards.

1st Team Academic All State
Garrett Gordon
Colton Tiffany

Honorable Mention Academic All-State
Matthew Maxson
Tom VanValkenburg

post_text: Hello Wildcats! This is Reagan and Candie, coaches of NHHS Cheer and Dance. Due to unforeseen circumstances, we are going to have to change things up this tryout season. The plan is to use technology to our advantage. At this point in the process, we need anyone who is interested to send an email to nhhs.cheer.dance@gmail.com with the following information: first and last name, grade level, phone number, and if you're trying out for both cheer and dance, or one or the other. We need this by April 6th. All information for the tryout process will be sent out via email from that point forward. We are excited to hear from you!

shared_text:
Lady Cat Softball
March 12 at 1:21 PM ¬∑

"Coach Dice, do you mind if I talk to your team for a few minutes? I was driving by and noticed how hard your team is working. Your team is hungry. They are covered in dirt. Diving after balls. Hustling. I just knew I had to stop and share a story and blessing."

Mr. Dave Hale played for the Chicago Bears from 1969-1974. He told the girls that one of his best sports memories was the summer he played softball and went undefeated and his coach bought ice cream for the entire team. The girls and I talked about the reference to ice cream as being a God wink.

Mr. Hale also talked about never giving up and how no one expected him to make it to the NFL. He wrapped up his talk and asked if he could give us an Irish blessing. He offered the blessing through tears and having to pause to collect himself. With a fist bump to the players and a kind but firm handshake to me and he was on his way.

We will never forget this practice! #unfinshedbusiness #ladycatsoftball #wildcatnation #godwink

post_text: 8th grade C.A.T.S. elective students were invited to present to the AARP group in Emporia at Presbyterian Manor. Mrs. Linda Van Gundy invited the group because she had read various articles in the Emporia Gazette about the civic engagement projects and recent civic engagement award. Students Sadie Bathurst, Austin Woodrow, Bethany DeDonder, and Lilly Parks talked about the success of their fundraising efforts as well as the passion for raising awareness about childhood cancer. Students shared information on their fundraising totals for the Never Let Go Fund as well as their recent accomplishments with the All Gold Day resolution passed by the Kansas House of Representatives. The AARP group was so impressed with the presentation and passion the students have for civic engagement they donated an additional $110 to Never Let Go Fund. Students were treated to ice cream after the luncheon.

post_text: What started as our first school-wide civic engagement project in C.A.T.S. back in August 2018 has reached levels beyond our comprehension! We are blown away by how passionate our students at NLC are about raising awareness. Our 8th graders along with Mr. Chanley, took the process of raising awareness to the next level by submitting our All Gold Day district wide proclamation and turning it into a state wide referendum. Never ever doubt what young students are capable of once they figure out their why! Wildcat nation is full of World Changers! üíõüíõüíõ Best quote from 8th grader Sadie Bathurst, "I hope that from today people realize that it is about raising awareness about childhood cancer and not about what a bunch of 8th graders did." - Folks, that is not something you can teach! These kids amaze us every single day!

post_text: Attention Middle School Parents/Guardians: Mrs. Adams would like the opportunity to hold math classes specifically for adults. The classes would focus on what the students are learning and techniques on how to help the student with their math homework. The classes would be in advance to the topic so that parents/guardians are prepared before the students might ask for help. The classes would be free. At this time we are just gauging interest so if you would be interested in something like this please email Mrs. Adams with your feedback (adamsa@usd251.org). Thank you for your time!

post_text: Today, NHHS seniors Morgan-Rae Paige, LeAnn Landis, and Southern Hall delivered a HUGE load of clothes, hygiene items, and non-perishable food donations to Plumb Place Women‚Äôs Refuge in Emporia. This donation drive was organized and executed by Morgan-Rae as a Personalized Learning Project, part of our Gemini Redesign Program. Morgan-Rae coordinated a competition among the classes and staff at Northern Heights and over the course of three weeks collected more donations than she could‚Äôve hoped for. Plumb Place Executive Director Mary Richardson was thrilled to receive the donations, saying how much it means to her staff and the women of Emporia. Way to go, Morgan-Rae! It‚Äôs a GREAT day to be a Wildcat!

USD 251 North Lyon County is seeking applications for Route, Activity and Substitute Bus Drivers.
Successful applicant(s) must have or be willing to obtain proper license requirements, pass drug/alcohol screening and background check.
Salary will be determined by experience. District pays $500 towards health insurance if drivers work over 17.5 hours a week.
Stay-at-home Mom's welcome!
Please call Stacie Horton at 620-481-2085 for more information.

post_text: Lyon County Emergency Communications Director Roxanne VanGundy visited with NLC 8th Grade Health students on the importance of 9-1-1. Students are currently learning basic first aid skills and how and when to call 9-1-1 in the event of an emergency. Director VanGundy discussed the advancements in 9-1-1 technology such as the ability to text 9-1-1 and address location. VanGundy also demonstrated the Emergency Medical Dispatch(EMD) protocol cards with students and discussed what to expect when you call 9-1-1.

post_text:
Northern Heights has entered into a co-op with Council Grove for wrestling. During the season they are wrestling as members of the Council Grove team, but come regional and state competition they will be listed as Northern Heights.
This year KSHSAA voted to make girls wrestling a sponsored sport. Girls now have their own division.
Season opened this week with a dual in Lyons on Thursday. This morning the boys traveled to Flint Hill HS where Grady Tiffany (freshman) placed 4th, Isiaiah Smith (junior) placed 2nd and Colton Tiffany (junior) placed 1st in their weight classes. Also wrestling, but not in attendance is Tristan Cullor.
The girls, Macie Wells (freshman) and Luzia Rulle (junior foreign exchange student), wrestled in Emporia. Luzia won her first ever match and Northern Heights first ever girls match by points in OT. Macie got 3rd place out of 4 girls. Excellent job by both girls against mostly 5A & 6A schools.

post_text:
Greetings from your new USD 251 district nurse!

I wanted to take a few moments to introduce myself to the parents and community of our district. My name is Ashley Keighley-Darbro. I have a background in both health promotion and nursing and have been working the last four years at Newman Regional Health in both the Emergency Department and NRHMP clinic. I‚Äôm very passionate about working with children and their families in regards to their healthcare and wellness so I‚Äôm thrilled to take on this role as your nurse. My husband, our two sons, and our two dogs live in the country outside of Americus and love being a part of this community! I‚Äôm looking forward to getting to know all of you better. If you have any questions, concerns, or would just like to reach out to talk to me individually about your child/children, please contact me via email at keighleya@usd251.org or by calling the NLC office on M/W/F or NHHS office on T/TH. As events, screenings, changes in schedules, or anything else comes up I will be in touch with you all more!
Thank you!
Mrs. Darbro
